### rag - explain RAG retrieval augmented generation
grade: **A** (content A, time penalty 0) - 39.4s vs 60s target
plan: 1 step(s) - research.deep=ok/37564ms

```
**Retrieval‑Augmented Generation (RAG)** is a two‑stage architecture that makes large‑language‑model (LLM) answers more factual and up‑to‑date by first **retrieving** relevant external information and then **generating** a response that is grounded in that material.

| Stage | What happens | Key components |
|-------|--------------|----------------|
| **Retrieval** | The user query is encoded into a vector and matched against embeddings of a pre‑indexed knowledge base (documents, APIs, databases, etc.). The most similar chunks are returned. | • External Knowledge Source  <br>• Text chunking & preprocessing  <br>• Embedding model  <br>• Vector database  <br>• Query encoder  <br>• Retriever |

```

